<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,802,1225]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,498,946,971]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Description &amp; Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Wingspan 
<quantity box="[626,750,946,970]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="2.8" metricValueMin="1.9" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="mm" value="23.5" valueMax="28.0" valueMin="19.0">19–28 mm</quantity>
. Forewing creamy white, with a short, curved, narrow apical dark grey line. Hindwing dirty white, without pattern (
<figureCitation box="[757,840,983,1007]" captionStart="FIGURES 16 – 21" captionStartId="31.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[268,1317,243,1881]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[243,1345,171,1895]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURES 16 – 21. Adult moths of Lithostege Hübner (left column, a: upperside, right column, b: underside). 16. L. notata (3, Sarkhoun, SW Iran); 17. L. fissurata fissurata (Ƥ, Roche de Sel, Algier); 18. L. fissurata inanis (Ƥ, Baluchistan, E Iran); 19. L. parva (3, Kopet-Dagh, Turkmenistan); 20. L. turkmenica (3, Karakum desert, Uzbekistan); 21. L. farinata (Ƥ, Sarepta, Russia). Scale bar: 10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279204/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[809,840,983,1007]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
). Tergite A– 
<number box="[981,993,983,1007]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="8.0">8</number>
(
<figureCitation box="[1007,1087,983,1007]" captionStart="FIGURES 45 – 47" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1914,1937]" captionTargetBox="[239,1355,239,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[209,1378,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 45 – 47. Lithostege Hübner: Male genitalia &amp; details of abdominal integument. 45. L. fissurata fissurata (gen. prep. 1608 H. R.; El Mesrane, Algeria), a: genital capsule, b: aedeagus, lateral view, c: 8 th tergite (left margin curved); 46. L. parva (gen. prep. 1021 H. R.; Kopet-Dagh, Turkmenistan), a: genital capsule, b: aedeagus, lateral view; 47. L. farinata (gen. prep. 1054 H. R.; Hamburg, Germany), a: genital capsule, b: aedeagus, lateral view, c: 8 th tergite. Scale bar: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279211/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[1059,1087,983,1007]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="45.0">45</number>
</figureCitation>
c) strongly sclerotised, distally prominent and irregularly crinkled. Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[743,829,1018,1042]" captionStart="FIGURES 45 – 47" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1914,1937]" captionTargetBox="[239,1355,239,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[209,1378,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 45 – 47. Lithostege Hübner: Male genitalia &amp; details of abdominal integument. 45. L. fissurata fissurata (gen. prep. 1608 H. R.; El Mesrane, Algeria), a: genital capsule, b: aedeagus, lateral view, c: 8 th tergite (left margin curved); 46. L. parva (gen. prep. 1021 H. R.; Kopet-Dagh, Turkmenistan), a: genital capsule, b: aedeagus, lateral view; 47. L. farinata (gen. prep. 1054 H. R.; Hamburg, Germany), a: genital capsule, b: aedeagus, lateral view, c: 8 th tergite. Scale bar: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279211/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[797,829,1018,1042]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="45.0">45</number>
</figureCitation>
): Valve with its larger, proximal part densely sclerotised, with a small, rounded l projection more ventrally on its outer margin; harpe a small, rounded, somewhat elongate lobe at base of valva, dorsal projection short, semicircular, with a pointed tip; aedeagus straight. Female genitalia (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Hausmann" box="[306,618,1127,1151]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" refString="Hausmann, A. &amp; Seguna, A. (2005) Lithostege fissurata Mabille, 1888 from Malta, new for the fauna of Europe (Geometridae, Larentiinae). Nota Lepidopterologica, 28 (1), 11 - 15." type="journal article" year="2005">
Hausmann &amp; Seguna, 
<number box="[558,618,1127,1151]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<number box="[629,659,1127,1151]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="12.0">12</number>
, fig. 
<number box="[716,730,1127,1151]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="3.0">3</number>
) very similar to those of 
<emphasis box="[1013,1223,1127,1151]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicName box="[1013,1220,1127,1151]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lithostege" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="fissurata" subSpecies="inanis">L. fissurata inanis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,802,1225]" box="[199,853,1162,1187]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
